  ],
  "text": "The Apache Kafka migration from the legacy consumer API to the modern KafkaConsumer API is centered on two internal implementation strategies for the ConsumerDelegate interface, which are selected at runtime via the ConsumerDelegateCreator factory based on the group protocol configuration.\n\nThe public KafkaConsumer API (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java) delegates to an internal ConsumerDelegate implementation, maintaining a stable interface while allowing multiple backend implementations. The Consumer interface (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/Consumer.java) defines the contract for all consumer operations including offset management methods: commitSync(), commitAsync(), seek(), and position().\n\nThere are two key ConsumerDelegate implementations:\n\n1. **ClassicKafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ClassicKafkaConsumer.java): Implements the classic group protocol (pre-KIP 848) for backward compatibility. This implementation uses synchronous, thread-blocking coordinator calls. The offset commit implementation at lines 741-754 calls coordinator.commitOffsetsSync() directly and waits for the result in the same thread. The async variant (lines 768-777) calls coordinator.commitOffsetsAsync() which returns immediately. Position management is handled synchronously via updateFetchPositions() (lines 1206-1218), which calls coordinator.initWithCommittedOffsetsIfNeeded() to fetch committed offsets.\n\n2. **AsyncKafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AsyncKafkaConsumer.java): Implements the new consumer group protocol (KIP 848) with an event-driven, background-thread architecture. The offset commit implementation is fundamentally different - commitSync() (lines 1577-1609) creates a SyncCommitEvent and enqueues it via an event handler to a background thread. It then awaits pending async commits via awaitPendingAsyncCommitsAndExecuteCommitCallbacks() (lines 1611-1634) before blocking on the future result. The commitAsync() variant (lines 896-922) creates an AsyncCommitEvent, enqueues it, and returns immediately with callbacks executed by a background thread. Position management uses CheckAndUpdatePositionsEvent which fetches committed offsets asynchronously.\n\n**Key Behavioral Differences in Offset Management**:\n\n- **Synchronization Model**: ClassicKafkaConsumer uses direct method calls with immediate blocking; AsyncKafkaConsumer uses event queues and background threads.\n- **Commit Ordering**: ClassicKafkaConsumer processes commits sequentially in the calling thread; AsyncKafkaConsumer must wait for pending async commits before executing new sync commits (awaitPendingAsyncCommitsAndExecuteCommitCallbacks).\n- **Position Updates**: ClassicKafkaConsumer fetches committed offsets synchronously during poll(); AsyncKafkaConsumer fetches them asynchronously via FetchCommittedOffsetsEvent.\n- **Callback Execution**: ClassicKafkaConsumer uses direct OffsetCommitCallback invocation; AsyncKafkaConsumer queues callbacks through OffsetCommitCallbackInvoker for background thread execution.\n- **Thread Safety**: ClassicKafkaConsumer uses currentThread atomic variable to enforce single-threaded access; AsyncKafkaConsumer uses acquireAndEnsureOpen() with background event processing.\n\nThe migration path is managed through ConsumerDelegateCreator, which selects the implementation based on the ConsumerConfig.GROUP_PROTOCOL_CONFIG setting: if set to GroupProtocol.CONSUMER, AsyncKafkaConsumer is used; otherwise, ClassicKafkaConsumer is used for backward compatibility."
}

